"McKenzie J.A.","Pluvial conditions in the eastern Sahara following the penultimate deglaciation: implications for changes in atmospheric circulation patterns with global warming",1993,"Palaeogeography, Palaeoclimatology, Palaeoecology","103","1-2",,"95","105",,,10.1016/0031-0182(93)90054-M,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0027845698&partnerID=40&md5=2fe00d1ac06c0e42b233b0f2e6a66403","Geological Institute, ETH-Zentrum, CH-8092 Zürich, Switzerland","McKenzie, J.A., Geological Institute, ETH-Zentrum, CH-8092 Zürich, Switzerland","During the transition from the penultimate glacial to the last interglacial period (Isotope Stages 6-5e or Terminal II), large freshwater lakes abruptly infilled sandy depressions in arid regions of the eastern Sahara. Geochemical and mineralogical studies of samples from lacustrine sequences in the Western Desert of southern Egypt indicate: (1) The sediments are chalk composed of authigenic chemical precipitates, predominantly low-Mg calcite, with carbonate contents averaging about 80%. The low dilution of the chemical precipitate by detrital input implies that physical erosion and transport of detrital grains were minimized by extensive vegetation cover in the catchment area. The fauna and flora associated with the lake deposits and Middle Paleolithic occupation sites on the paleo-shorelines attest to a more amenable environment. (2) Vastly different rainfall or atmospheric circulation patterns than at present must have existed based on consistently negative δ18OPDB values for the chalk, as low as -9.5‰, which would require precipitation from lake waters significantly more depleted in 18O than the modern local spring water (δ18OSMOW= -1.8‰). (3) The lakes were stable perennial water bodies with relatively long residence times sufficient to produce isotopic covariant signals in the chalks. Apparently, the lakes disappeared as abruptly as they appeared without going through a terminal phase of evaporative enrichment. Extremely arid conditions again prevailed. During the transition from the last glacial to the present interglacial (Terminal I), a similar change from arid to pluvial conditions occurred. Thus, it is proposed that, during transitions from glacial to interglacial climates, rapid global warming can lead to temporary alteration to atmospheric circulation with an intersification of the southwest monsoons, bringing large quantities of isotopically light moisture to the Eastern Sahara. © 1993.",,"atmospheric circulation; global warming; penultimate deglaciation; pluvial conditions; Egypt, Western Desert",,,,,,"Dansgaard, Stable isotopes in precipitation (1964) Tellus, 16, pp. 436-468; Epstein, Mayeda, Variations of O18 content of waters from natural sources (1953) Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta, 4, pp. 213-224; Eugster, Hardie, Saline lakes (1978) Lakes, Chemistry, Geology, Physics, pp. 237-293. , A. Lerman, Springer, Berlin; Fritz, Anderson, Lewis, Late Quaternary climatic trends and history of Lake Erie from stable isotopes studies (1975) Science, 190, pp. 267-269; Gat, The isotope of hydrogen and oxygen in precipitation (1980) Handbook of Environmental Isotope Geochemistry, 1, pp. 221-247. , Elsevier, Amsterdam; Hill, Sedimentology of Pleistocene deposits associated with Middle Paleolithic sites in Bir Tarfawi and Bir Sahara East (1993) Egypt During the Last Interglacial: The Middle Paleolithic of Bir Tarfawi and Bir Sahara East, pp. 66-105. , F. Wendorf, R. Schild, A.E. Close, Plenum Press, New York; Imhof, (1948) Schweizerischer Mittelschulatlas, p. 144. , 9th ed., Orell Füssli, Zürich; Kelts, Environments of deposition of lacustrine petroleum source rocks: an introduction (1988) Lacustrine Petroleum Source Rocks, pp. 3-26. , A.J. Fleet, K. Kelts, M.R. Talbot, Blackwell, Oxford; Kelts, Hsü, Freshwater carbonate sedimentation (1978) Lakes, Chemistry, Geology, Physics, pp. 295-353. , A. Lerman, Springer, Berlin; Lee, McKenzie, Sturm, Carbon isotope fractionation and changes in the